Note:
SwiftUI Emitter - Buffered output for SwiftUI code generation

All buffer management, character/string emission, and indentation logic
is delegated to the shared byte-buffer foundation in emitter_common.runa.

Conventions:
- 4-space indentation per Apple Swift style guide
- Null-terminated output strings
:End Note

Import "../emitter_common.runa" as EmitterCommon

@Reasoning:
SwiftUI is structurally Swift, so the emitter only needs the shared byte
buffer plus a thin type wrapper that gives callers a SwiftUI-named handle.
Keeping the struct distinct from SwiftEmitter prevents accidental cross-use
in the dispatch tables of hir_to_swiftui.runa.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three fields shadow the layout of the raw emitter in emitter_common.runa
(buffer pointer, allocated capacity, current length). The actual storage
lives in the EmitterCommon arena; this struct exists only as a typed
handle for the translation backend.
@End Implementation

Type called "SwiftUIEmitter":
    buffer as Integer
    capacity as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Factory entry that hides the shared emitter dependency from
hir_to_swiftui.runa so the backend never imports EmitterCommon directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_create which allocates an initial byte buffer
(default capacity selected by EmitterCommon) and zeroes the length.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_swiftui_emitter" returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_create from EmitterCommon
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirrors create_swiftui_emitter so the caller has a symmetric lifecycle
pair and never has to touch raw deallocation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_destroy which frees the byte buffer then the
emitter struct itself. Returns the EmitterCommon status code unchanged.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Caller must guarantee the handle was produced by create_swiftui_emitter
and has not already been destroyed; double-free is the caller's bug, not
the emitter's responsibility.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_swiftui_emitter" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_destroy from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the growth hook so call sites that know they are about to emit a
large literal can pre-size the buffer and avoid repeated realloc churn.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to emitter_raw_ensure_capacity which grows the buffer to at
least the requested byte count using EmitterCommon's doubling policy.
@End Implementation

Process called "ensure_capacity" takes emitter as Integer, needed as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_ensure_capacity from EmitterCommon with emitter, needed
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-byte emission is the hot primitive for punctuation, braces, and
operators in the SwiftUI output, so it is exposed as its own entry rather
than forcing callers to allocate one-character strings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards the byte value to emitter_raw_emit_byte, which appends after
ensuring capacity for at least one more byte.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Hot path. O(1) amortized; called once per emitted character of SwiftUI
source.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_char" takes emitter as Integer, char as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bulk emission for keywords, identifiers, and pre-formatted fragments;
strictly faster than looping emit_char from the caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_string which walks the null-terminated input
and copies bytes into the buffer, growing as needed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Hot path. O(n) in input length with one capacity check per grow event.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_string" takes emitter as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience for the common pattern of emitting a SwiftUI statement
followed by a newline; avoids forcing callers to emit the terminator
separately.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the string then appends ASCII LF (10) as the line terminator. Swift
tooling on all supported platforms accepts LF, matching the project's
LF-only convention.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_line" takes emitter as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, str
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dedicated helper because spaces are emitted between every identifier and
operator pair; keeping the literal 32 in one place avoids magic numbers
in the backend.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits ASCII SPACE (32) as a single byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_space" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
Apple's Swift API Design Guidelines and SwiftUI sample code both use
4-space indentation; the emitter materializes that directly instead of
relying on a post-pass formatter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Multiplies the logical indent level by 4 to obtain the space count, then
emits that many ASCII SPACE bytes in a tight loop. No string allocation.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(level) bytes emitted. Called once per emitted statement; level rarely
exceeds 6 in practice so the loop is short.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_indent" takes emitter as Integer, level as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 4-space indentation per Apple Swift style guide.
    Let total_spaces be level multiplied by 4
    Let count be 0
    While count is less than total_spaces:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
        Set count to count plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the accumulated SwiftUI source as a null-terminated string so the
driver can hand it to disk I/O or further processing without copying.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_get_output which terminates the buffer and
returns its base pointer. Caller does not own the pointer; lifetime is
tied to the emitter handle.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Returned pointer aliases the emitter's internal buffer. Caller must not
free it directly and must not use it after destroy_swiftui_emitter.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_output" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the current byte count so callers (e.g., golden-output diff
tools) can detect empty or unexpectedly short generation results.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_length which reads the stored length field.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_length" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_length from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lets the driver reuse a single emitter across multiple translation units
without paying allocation cost for each one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_reset which zeroes the length field but keeps
the buffer allocation intact for reuse.
@End Implementation

Process called "reset" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_reset from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process
